      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Medication</th>
          <th>Class</th>
          <th>Key Nursing Points</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Carbidopa-levodopa (Sinemet) 25/100 mg PO TID</strong></td>
          <td>Dopamine precursor</td>
          <td>⚠️ CRITICAL — on-time administration; "off" episodes if missed or delayed; assess swallowing before each dose (dysphagia common); avoid antipsychotics (dopamine antagonists — worsen Parkinson's); separate from high-protein meals (protein reduces absorption); extremely high fall risk (shuffling gait + orthostatic hypotension)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole (Bactrim DS) PO BID</strong></td>
          <td>Antibiotic — sulfonamide</td>
          <td>UTI treatment; monitor for allergic reaction (rash, Stevens-Johnson syndrome — rare but serious); monitor renal function and CBC; ensure adequate hydration; verify no sulfa allergy before administration; complete full course</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Docusate sodium PO daily</strong></td>
          <td>Stool softener</td>
          <td>Constipation prevention — Parkinson's autonomic dysfunction significantly increases constipation risk; safe in elderly; monitor bowel function daily; encourage adequate fluid and dietary fiber intake</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- APPENDIX B -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-b">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge phase-badge-appendix">Appendix B</span>
      <h2>Post-Simulation Discussion Questions</h2>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q1: What is the most important nursing action when elder abuse is suspected?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>The most important nursing action is to ensure the patient's immediate safety and complete a <strong>mandatory report to Adult Protective Services (APS)</strong>. You do not need proof — only reasonable suspicion is required by law. Immediate steps: (1) ensure patient is not alone with the suspected abuser; (2) notify the charge nurse; (3) contact social work immediately; (4) notify the provider and document findings objectively; (5) complete the APS report per your state's requirements. Do not confront or accuse the caregiver — the investigation is APS's role, not the nurse's.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q2: How does the nurse assess for abuse without the caregiver present?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>Use a <strong>policy-based rationale</strong> to request private time: "It's our standard admission policy to assess all patients privately for a few minutes." This is non-accusatory and gives the caregiver a face-saving reason to leave. Once alone, use open-ended questions: "How have things been at home?" / "How did these bruises happen?" / "Are you safe at home?" Do not pressure the patient for disclosure — she may not feel safe enough to disclose yet. Document what you observe objectively regardless of her verbal response. The physical findings themselves are reportable evidence.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q3: What injury pattern is most suspicious for physical abuse in the elderly?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>Most suspicious patterns: (1) <strong>Multiple bruises in different stages of healing</strong> — indicates repeated trauma over time; (2) <strong>Atypical locations</strong> — bilateral upper arms, torso, buttocks, back, inner thighs (accidental injuries are on shins, knees, and forearms); (3) <strong>Bilateral symmetric injuries</strong> — both arms bruised simultaneously suggests being grabbed; (4) <strong>Pattern injuries</strong> — bruises matching an object shape; (5) <strong>Explanation inconsistent with injury</strong> — "she falls" but the bruises are on her upper arms, not her shins. In Gwen's case, bilateral upper arm bruising across multiple healing stages is highly concerning for repeated physical abuse.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q4: Why is carbidopa-levodopa administration considered a patient safety priority?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>Carbidopa-levodopa is the primary dopamine replacement therapy for Parkinson's disease. When doses are missed or delayed, dopamine levels drop and the patient experiences a sudden "off" episode: severe rigidity, freezing, inability to move or speak, and dysphagia. These episodes can be frightening and dangerous — the patient may be unable to swallow safely, significantly increasing aspiration risk. On-time administration maintains stable dopamine levels and prevents these episodes. In the hospital setting, nursing staff must be aware that Parkinson's medications cannot be held or delayed without specific provider orders, as this constitutes a patient safety risk distinct from most other medications.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q5: What antipsychotics are relatively safe in Parkinson's disease?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>Most antipsychotics (both typical and atypical) are dopamine antagonists and are <strong>contraindicated</strong> in Parkinson's disease because they block dopamine receptors and dramatically worsen motor symptoms (rigidity, freezing, akinesia).</p>
        <p>The two antipsychotics considered relatively safe in Parkinson's disease:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Quetiapine (Seroquel)</strong> — preferred; low dopamine D2 affinity; less likely to worsen motor symptoms</li>
          <li><strong>Clozapine</strong> — most evidence for safety in Parkinson's psychosis, but requires mandatory REMS monitoring (CBC weekly) due to agranulocytosis risk</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Always consult pharmacist and provider before administering any antipsychotic to a patient with Parkinson's disease. Document the rationale for use clearly.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

